5) Comparison tables

Table A — Blockchains: nodes / clients / consensus (concise)

Network	Node roles (brief)	Example clients / software	Consensus

Bitcoin	Full nodes, miners, light clients	Bitcoin Core (reference)	Proof-of-Work (PoW) (mining, longest valid chain). 
Ethereum	Execution nodes, consensus (beacon) nodes, validators	Geth, Besu (execution); Prysm, Lighthouse, Teku (consensus).	Proof-of-Stake (PoS) validators (post-Merge). 
Solana	Validators, RPC nodes	Solana validator binary / official stack	PoH (timestamping) + PoS leader selection (high-TPS design). 
Polkadot	Relay validators, collators, nominators	Parity Polkadot client (Substrate)	BABE (block production) + GRANDPA (finality); PoS staking. 
Hyperledger Fabric	Peers, orderers, CAs	Fabric peer/orderer binaries; Fabric SDKs	Pluggable (CFT/BFT options); permissioned; no native token required. 


Table B — Tokens / NFTs: examples & key notes

Example	Type	Chain / Standard	Why it matters (short)

BAYC	NFT (ERC-721)	Ethereum	Cultural/status asset; shows IP & community utility. 
NBA Top Shot	NFT (Flow)	Flow	Licensed sports collectibles at scale; Flow built for consumer UX. 
CryptoKitties	NFT	Ethereum	Early NFT viral case; demonstrated congestion risk. 
Axie Infinity	NFT + fungible tokens (AXS, SLP)	Ethereum / Ronin	Example of complex gaming economy & market risk. 
USDC	Fungible stablecoin (ERC-20)	Multi-chain (Ethereum primary)	Real-world pegged value; payments & DeFi backbone. 
RealT tokens	Fungible tokens (security/asset tokens)	Ethereum (ERC-20 variants)	Real-asset fractional ownership; legal structuring required. 
SPL tokens (USDC on Solana)	Fungible tokens	Solana SPL	Example of high-TPS fungible token use case. 



---

6) Risks, tradeoffs & practical notes (short)

Scalability vs decentralization: High-TPS chains (Solana, special layer-2s) trade some decentralization/design choices for throughput. Ethereum’s transition to PoS changed node client architecture and validator economics. 

Security & economic risks: Token economies (Axie, play-to-earn) can create fragile markets; smart contract hacks and bridges remain major attack vectors. 

Legal & compliance: Tokenizing real assets (RealT) requires careful legal structuring — tokens often represent contractual rights rather than automatic legal title
